# 15. Tail Recursion

Recursive call is the last statement.

```java
static void fun(int n) {

    if(n == 0)
        return;

    fun(n - 1);
}
```

✔ Easier to optimize

---

# 16. Non-Tail Recursion

Work remains after recursive call.

```java
static void fun(int n) {

    if(n == 0)
        return;

    fun(n - 1);

    System.out.println(n);
}
```

---

# 17. Direct Recursion

Function calls itself.

```java
fun()
{
    fun();
}
```

---

# 18. Indirect Recursion

Functions call each other.

```java
void A() {
    B();
}

void B() {
    A();
}
```

---

# 19. Why StackOverflowError Happens

Occurs when recursion never reaches base case.

Example:

```java
void fun() {
    fun();
}
```

Result:

```
StackOverflowError
```

